Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.74,0:02:19.22,1080P_CN_Up,,0,0,0,,第一行：1959年 9月\N第二行：苏维埃社会主义共和国联盟
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.68,0:04:14.78,1080P_CN_Up,,0,0,0,,也就是后来的“J002E3”
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.80,0:09:39.34,1080P_CN_Up,,0,800,700,,“这是在1972年4月20日登陆月球的，\N来自地球的宇航员查尔斯·杜克的全家”
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.92,0:13:47.80,1080P_CN_Up,,0,0,0,,字幕翻译给虫，欢迎点赞投币收藏分享转发评论关注充电~
Dialogue: 1,0:00:00.38,0:00:05.37,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,85,,{\fs57}2019年1月3日，中国嫦娥4号月球探测器携带玉兔2号月球车在月球背面软着陆
Dialogue: 2,0:00:00.38,0:00:05.37,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,50,,With the surprise landing of a Chinese Rover Yutu 2 or the Jade rabbit 2
Dialogue: 1,0:00:05.48,0:00:10.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,85,,{\fs57}2019年1月3日，中国嫦娥4号月球探测器携带玉兔2号月球车在月球背面软着陆
Dialogue: 2,0:00:05.48,0:00:10.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,50,,and the Chang'e lander on the far side of a Moon on the 3rd of January 2019,
Dialogue: 1,0:00:11.10,0:00:15.52,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,我打算好好统计一下人类在月球上留下了什么东西
Dialogue: 2,0:00:11.10,0:00:15.52,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,I thought it'd be interesting to see what sort of things we've actually put up on the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:00:15.72,0:00:19.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,并推测一下它们将来会怎样
Dialogue: 2,0:00:15.72,0:00:19.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and to speculate on what might happen to them in the future.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:32.42,0:00:38.22,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗任务在月球表面上留下了最多的东西，这点是毋庸置疑的
Dialogue: 2,0:00:32.42,0:00:38.22,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Now it will come as no surprise that the Apollo missions have left behind the most amount of items
Dialogue: 1,0:00:38.34,0:00:40.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但在说到阿波罗任务之前
Dialogue: 2,0:00:38.34,0:00:40.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,but long before they were even thought of,
Dialogue: 1,0:00:40.76,0:00:45.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,苏联在很久之前就把东西送上月球，美国人不止一次以为苏联做不到
Dialogue: 2,0:00:40.76,0:00:45.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the Soviets pulled off something that not for the first time the U.S. thought they couldn't actually do.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:46.70,0:00:51.46,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在1959年，苏联的月球2号探测器成为了首个
Dialogue: 2,0:00:46.70,0:00:51.46,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,In 1959 the Soviet Luna 2 probe was the first man-made object
Dialogue: 1,0:00:51.46,0:00:54.40,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,主动撞机月球表面的人造物体
Dialogue: 2,0:00:51.46,0:00:54.40,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,to intentionally impact on to the lunar surface,
Dialogue: 1,0:00:54.76,0:00:58.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,而当时美国离月球最近的探测任务是先驱4号
Dialogue: 2,0:00:54.76,0:00:58.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,the closest to the US had got to the Moon by then was with a pioneer 4,
Dialogue: 1,0:00:59.04,0:01:01.14,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,而它也只是在六万公里外飞跃月球
Dialogue: 2,0:00:59.04,0:01:01.14,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,but that was 60,000 kilometers away,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:01.38,0:01:03.98,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,这让美国人有点震惊，因为美国人认为
Dialogue: 2,0:01:01.38,0:01:03.98,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,which was a bit of a shock because the U.S. believed that
Dialogue: 1,0:01:03.98,0:01:10.50,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,虽然当时苏联有更大的火箭，但他们导航和制导精度不够
Dialogue: 2,0:01:03.98,0:01:10.50,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,while the Soviets had bigger rockets, they were lacking the precision in their navigation and guidance systems.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:11.06,0:01:16.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,虽然这些早期的探测器撞月任务更多的是宣传意义
Dialogue: 2,0:01:11.06,0:01:16.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Although these early probes were designed to crash into the Moon in a piece of pure propaganda,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:16.48,0:01:22.39,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但月球2号还是留下了一张名片告诉后人他们是先来的
Dialogue: 2,0:01:16.48,0:01:22.39,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Luna 2 left behind a calling card to remind everyone else that they were here first.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:22.96,0:01:27.42,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,月球2号除了一些实验设备，还带了两个球
Dialogue: 2,0:01:22.96,0:01:27.42,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Luna 2 was loaded not only with experiments but two small spheres,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:27.56,0:01:31.56,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,一个直径7.5厘米，一个12厘米
Dialogue: 2,0:01:27.56,0:01:31.56,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,one 7.5 cm and the other 12 cm across,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:31.76,0:01:37.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,每个上面都印有五边形的苏联国徽
Dialogue: 2,0:01:31.76,0:01:37.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and made from pentagonal pennants, each stamped with the insignia of the Soviet Union,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:37.18,0:01:40.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,大球上还印有“1959”
Dialogue: 2,0:01:37.18,0:01:40.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and the date 1959 on the larger of the two.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:40.64,0:01:47.44,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,球体中心有爆炸物，可以在撞击时把国徽散播在月球的土地上
Dialogue: 2,0:01:40.64,0:01:47.44,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,These spheres had an explosive core and were designed to explode and scatter the pennants on impact.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:47.98,0:01:53.02,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,作为第一个到达月球的人造物体，它们后来的命运就不好说了
Dialogue: 2,0:01:47.98,0:01:53.02,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Although these were the very first man-made items to make it to the Moon their fate is unknown.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:53.02,0:02:01.82,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,因为月球2号当时以每秒3.3公里、每小时12000公里的速度撞击月球
Dialogue: 2,0:01:53.02,0:02:01.82,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,As Luna 2 impacted a speed of around 3.3 km/s about 12,000 kilometers an hour
Dialogue: 1,0:02:01.92,0:02:04.40,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,估计在撞击瞬间就灰飞烟灭了
Dialogue: 2,0:02:01.92,0:02:04.40,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and was probably vaporized on impact.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:04.92,0:02:10.06,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,第三个球在月球2号的火箭里，发射三十分钟后落回地球
Dialogue: 2,0:02:04.92,0:02:10.06,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,A third sphere was in the Luna 2's rocket body which crashed about 30 minutes later
Dialogue: 1,0:02:10.32,0:02:14.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,里面装有液体和一条铝条，上面印有1959年
Dialogue: 2,0:02:10.32,0:02:14.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,that was filled with liquid and aluminum strips with the year 1959
Dialogue: 1,0:02:14.90,0:02:18.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,和“苏维埃社会主义共和国联盟”字样
Dialogue: 2,0:02:14.90,0:02:18.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and Union of Soviet Socialist Republics engraved upon them.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:19.36,0:02:23.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,随着太空竞赛的加剧，人们对月球的研究也随之进步
Dialogue: 2,0:02:19.36,0:02:23.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,As the space race intensified the lunar research also increased.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:23.48,0:02:27.70,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,美国发射了徘徊者号探测器近距离拍摄了月球照片
Dialogue: 2,0:02:23.48,0:02:27.70,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,The U.S. sent the Ranger probes to take close-up images of the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:27.88,0:02:31.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,他们也和苏联一样让探测器撞击月球
Dialogue: 2,0:02:27.88,0:02:31.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,They did this like the soviet lunar probes by crashing into the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:02:31.76,0:02:35.18,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,并在同时向地球实时传输视频信号
Dialogue: 2,0:02:31.76,0:02:35.18,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,whilst transmitting live TV signals back to Earth.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:35.46,0:02:38.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,有段时间这个项目被称为“射就完事了”
Dialogue: 2,0:02:35.46,0:02:38.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,At one point it was called the "shoot and hope" program
Dialogue: 1,0:02:38.32,0:02:43.16,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,因为九个徘徊者号探测器的前六个有的在发射台炸了(1、2号)
Dialogue: 2,0:02:38.32,0:02:43.16,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,because the first six out of nine range probes either failed on the launch pad,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:43.26,0:02:47.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,有的彻底错过月球(3、5号)，有的还没到月球摄像机坏了(6号)
Dialogue: 2,0:02:43.26,0:02:47.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,missed the Moon completely or failed before reaching the Moon's surface.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:48.28,0:02:51.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,之后美国启动了勘测者计划
Dialogue: 2,0:02:48.28,0:02:51.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,This was followed up by the surveyor program
Dialogue: 1,0:02:51.16,0:02:55.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,来了解月球表面更多信息，并为阿波罗任务选择潜在的着陆点
Dialogue: 2,0:02:51.16,0:02:55.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,to find out more about the actual surface and potential landing sites for Apollo.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:55.96,0:03:01.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,当时有人担心着陆到月球的探测器会“沉没”在月尘中
Dialogue: 2,0:02:55.96,0:03:01.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,as it was feared by some but any Lander would just sink and disappear into the lunar dust.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:01.78,0:03:07.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,七个勘测者号探测器中的五个成功着陆，证明了之前的担忧是多余的
Dialogue: 2,0:03:01.78,0:03:07.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Five out of the seven surveyors successfully landed and proved that theory was groundless.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:08.42,0:03:15.66,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,与此同时，NASA启动月球轨道计划，成为NASA首个环绕勘探月球
Dialogue: 2,0:03:08.42,0:03:15.66,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Also around this time, the lunar orbiter program was the first NASA craft orbit and survey the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:03:15.66,0:03:20.44,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,任务包括为阿波罗任务绘制月球重力场地图
Dialogue: 2,0:03:15.66,0:03:20.44,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,including mapping its gravitational field again for the Apollo missions.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:21.00,0:03:26.68,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在任务完成后，月球轨道探测器离轨，撞击月球
Dialogue: 2,0:03:21.00,0:03:26.68,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,After their missions were complete, the orbiters were deorbited and crashed into the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:03:26.68,0:03:29.40,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,以保证它们不会威胁阿波罗任务
Dialogue: 2,0:03:26.68,0:03:29.40,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,so they wouldn't pose any threat to the Apollo missions.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:29.66,0:03:34.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,美国那边的月球轨道探测器1、2、3号撞击月球背面
Dialogue: 2,0:03:29.66,0:03:34.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,With lunar orbiters one, two and three ending up on the far side of the Moon,
Dialogue: 1,0:03:34.92,0:03:41.56,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在前四次软着陆尝试失败的情况下，苏联这边成功率看着不怎么靠谱
Dialogue: 2,0:03:34.92,0:03:41.56,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the Soviets had a seemingly hit and miss success rate with the first four attempts of a soft landing failed.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:41.94,0:03:50.53,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,{\fs62}终于在1966年2月3日，月球9号探测器成为人类首个月球软着陆的探测器
Dialogue: 2,0:03:41.94,0:03:50.53,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Finally on the 3rd Feb 1966 lunar 9 became the first lunar lander to achieve and survive a soft landing.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:51.04,0:03:57.04,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,人们常常忽视的一点是：送飞船上天的火箭也会坠毁月球
Dialogue: 2,0:03:51.04,0:03:57.04,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Something which is often overlooked is the rockets that carried the spacecraft also ended up on the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:57.64,0:04:07.94,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗11、13到17号的土星五号火箭三级最终都坠毁在月球
Dialogue: 2,0:03:57.64,0:04:07.94,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The third stage of the Saturn V that carried the Apollo missions 11, 13, 14, 15, 16 and 17 also crashed into the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:04:08.08,0:04:10.44,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,有些落点还很有名
Dialogue: 2,0:04:08.08,0:04:10.44,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and some of their positions are well known.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:10.68,0:04:14.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗12号的三级本来要去绕日轨道
Dialogue: 2,0:04:10.68,0:04:14.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Apollo 12 third stage was planned to go into a solar orbit
Dialogue: 1,0:04:14.92,0:04:18.72,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但由于燃料箱排出的燃料让它没有足够剩余燃料
Dialogue: 2,0:04:14.92,0:04:18.72,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,but due to venting of his fuel tanks it didn't have enough propellant
Dialogue: 1,0:04:18.82,0:04:22.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,最终三级进入了地月之间的稳定轨道中
Dialogue: 2,0:04:18.82,0:04:22.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and ended up in a stable orbit between the Earth and the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:22.76,0:04:29.42,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,虽然阿波罗13号没有登月，但它用过的三级也检测到了撞击月球
Dialogue: 2,0:04:22.76,0:04:29.42,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Even though Apollo 13 never landed, its spent third stage was detected hitting the surface
Dialogue: 1,0:04:29.56,0:04:34.82,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,撞击坑被月球勘测轨道飞行器相机拍到
Dialogue: 2,0:04:29.56,0:04:34.82,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and the impact crater has been captured by the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter camera
Dialogue: 1,0:04:34.94,0:04:39.34,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,撞击点位于阿波罗12号着陆点135公里处
Dialogue: 2,0:04:34.94,0:04:39.34,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,some 135 kilometers away from the Apollo 12 site.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:39.92,0:04:47.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗12号以后的所有任务都在月球留下了阿波罗月球表面实验包
Dialogue: 2,0:04:39.92,0:04:47.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Apollo 12 and all the following missions left behind the ALSEP or Apollo Lunar Surface Experiments Package.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:48.00,0:04:54.92,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,内含一系列实验仪器，包括用于检测阿波罗13号三级撞击的月震仪
Dialogue: 2,0:04:48.00,0:04:54.92,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,This included a range of experiments like the seismometer which picked up the Apollo 13 third-stage impact
Dialogue: 1,0:04:55.16,0:04:59.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,还有其他设备，比如检测微陨石的
Dialogue: 2,0:04:55.16,0:04:59.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,as well as other devices through the analysis of micro meteorites,
Dialogue: 1,0:04:59.64,0:05:05.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,月球重力、磁场、太阳辐射、大气和内部结构的
Dialogue: 2,0:04:59.64,0:05:05.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,the Moon's gravity, magnetic field, solar radiation, atmosphere and internal structure.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:05.76,0:05:10.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,阿波罗11号在月球上放置了月球激光测距实验仪
Dialogue: 2,0:05:05.76,0:05:10.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,Apollo 11 left behind the lunar laser ranging experiment
Dialogue: 1,0:05:10.48,0:05:14.34,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,它是今天唯一一个仍然可用的实验仪器
Dialogue: 2,0:05:10.48,0:05:14.34,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,which is the only lunar experiment still to be working today
Dialogue: 1,0:05:14.50,0:05:19.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,使用地球上的激光就可以测量地月距离
Dialogue: 2,0:05:14.50,0:05:19.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and uses an Earth-based laser to measure the distance from the Earth to the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:05:19.08,0:05:21.54,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,精度可达3厘米
Dialogue: 2,0:05:19.08,0:05:21.54,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,with an accuracy of about three centimeters.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:22.16,0:05:27.40,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗任务中，登月舱整个着陆月球，但没法整个离开
Dialogue: 2,0:05:22.16,0:05:27.40,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The Apollo missions landed with a complete lander but they couldn't return in the same way,
Dialogue: 1,0:05:27.66,0:05:31.98,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,只有登月舱上升级能带着宇航员起飞离开月球
Dialogue: 2,0:05:27.66,0:05:31.98,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,only the ascent stage of the lander took off to return the crew
Dialogue: 1,0:05:32.20,0:05:38.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,且有着非常严格的重量限制，超重可能就没法飞回指令舱了
Dialogue: 2,0:05:32.20,0:05:38.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and they had a very strict weight limits, too much weight and they might not make it back to the command module
Dialogue: 1,0:05:38.72,0:05:42.10,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,真正意义上的差一公斤都不行
Dialogue: 2,0:05:38.72,0:05:42.10,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,literally every kilogram made a difference,
Dialogue: 1,0:05:42.48,0:05:48.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这也是为啥会留下一堆看似随机的物品清单，我们稍后会看到该清单
Dialogue: 2,0:05:42.48,0:05:48.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and that was a reason for leaving behind the seemingly random list of objects as we will see later.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:48.72,0:05:53.20,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,当宇航员从登月舱上升级回到指令舱
Dialogue: 2,0:05:48.72,0:05:53.20,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Once the crews had transferred from the ascent module to the command module,
Dialogue: 1,0:05:53.30,0:05:59.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,上升级会再次分离并坠毁在月球，除了两个例外
Dialogue: 2,0:05:53.30,0:05:59.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the ascent modules were released to crash back onto the lunar surface except 2.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:59.70,0:06:04.44,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗13号登月舱变成宇航员返回地球的“救生艇”
Dialogue: 2,0:05:59.70,0:06:04.44,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Apollo 13 which was used as a lifeboat to get the crew back to Earth
Dialogue: 1,0:06:04.54,0:06:08.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,最终在地球大气中烧毁，另一个例外是阿波罗10号
Dialogue: 2,0:06:04.54,0:06:08.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and burned up in the Earth's atmosphere and Apollo 10.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:08.78,0:06:15.14,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗10号是阿波罗11号除着陆以外的完整彩排
Dialogue: 2,0:06:08.78,0:06:15.14,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Apollo 10 was a complete dress rehearsal for Apollo 11 except for the landing.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:15.46,0:06:23.16,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,{\fs62}尤金·塞尔南和托马斯·斯塔福德驾驶登月舱到月球表面15公里高处后返回
Dialogue: 2,0:06:15.46,0:06:23.16,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Eugene Cernan and Thomas Stafford took the lunar lander to within 15 kilometers of the surface before returning.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:23.46,0:06:30.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,实际上那次任务里上升级故意少装了燃料，防止宇航员尝试登陆月球
Dialogue: 2,0:06:23.46,0:06:30.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,In fact the ascent stage was deliberately short fueled to stop the crew from attempting a landing on the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:06:30.70,0:06:34.88,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,因为那样的话他们就没有足够燃料回到指令舱了
Dialogue: 2,0:06:30.70,0:06:34.88,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,because if they did they wouldn't have enough fuel to make it back to the command module.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:35.44,0:06:42.18,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗10号登月舱下降级留在了轨道，没有坠毁月球，位置未知
Dialogue: 2,0:06:35.44,0:06:42.18,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The Apollo 10 descent stage was left in orbit but fell back to the Moon and it's position is unknown.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:42.36,0:06:46.58,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在宇航员离开“史努比”号登月舱后
Dialogue: 2,0:06:42.36,0:06:46.58,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,After the crew had transferred the ascent stage nicknamed "Snoopy",
Dialogue: 1,0:06:46.70,0:06:49.28,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,他们点燃了登月舱的发动机使其耗尽燃料
Dialogue: 2,0:06:46.70,0:06:49.28,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,fired its engine until it ran out of fuel.
Dialogue: 1,0:06:49.38,0:06:53.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这一操作让它进入了绕日轨道并至今仍在那条轨道上
Dialogue: 2,0:06:49.38,0:06:53.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,This sent it out into an orbit around the Sun, and it's still there,
Dialogue: 1,0:06:53.78,0:06:57.14,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在一条比地球略小的绕日轨道的某个位置上
Dialogue: 2,0:06:53.78,0:06:57.14,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,somewhere, in an orbit slightly shorter than that of the Earth,
Dialogue: 1,0:06:57.28,0:07:02.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,它也成为唯一一个曾经载人并留在太空的飞船
Dialogue: 2,0:06:57.28,0:07:02.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the only manned spacecraft left in space without a crew.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:02.26,0:07:05.92,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,如果你看每次任务留在月球的东西列表
Dialogue: 2,0:07:02.26,0:07:05.92,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,If you look at the inventory of items left behind for each mission
Dialogue: 1,0:07:06.00,0:07:08.96,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,你能看到一大堆相当普通的东西
Dialogue: 2,0:07:06.00,0:07:08.96,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,you'll see a lot of really rather mundane items.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:09.16,0:07:15.42,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,比如过滤器、尿液、粪便袋、食物包、座椅扶手、毛巾
Dialogue: 2,0:07:09.16,0:07:15.42,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Things like filters, urine and defecation bags, food bags, chair arm rests, towels,
Dialogue: 1,0:07:15.42,0:07:22.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,电池、耳塞、牙刷、靴子、钳子、工具、秤，超过八百个
Dialogue: 2,0:07:15.42,0:07:22.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,batteries, earplugs, brushes, boots, tongs, tools, scales in fact over eight hundred items.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:22.62,0:07:27.02,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,NASA专门列了一份22页的清单记录留在月球的东西
Dialogue: 2,0:07:22.62,0:07:27.02,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,NASA has created a 22-page-document listing everything on the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:07:27.10,0:07:29.98,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,你可以下载下来细细查看
Dialogue: 2,0:07:27.10,0:07:29.98,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,which you can download and peruse for yourself.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:02.26,0:07:29.98,1080P_CN_Up,,0,0,0,,视频说明有该清单下载链接
Dialogue: 1,0:07:30.58,0:07:33.82,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有些东西你可能以为他们本该带回来
Dialogue: 2,0:07:30.58,0:07:33.82,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,But there are also some things that you think they would like to bring back
Dialogue: 1,0:07:33.82,0:07:39.94,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,比如每个平均拍1500张照片的哈苏相机
Dialogue: 2,0:07:33.82,0:07:39.94,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,like the Hasselblad cameras which were used to take on average 1500 photos each
Dialogue: 1,0:07:40.00,0:07:45.22,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但阿波罗任务使用的14个中有12个被留在月球
Dialogue: 2,0:07:40.00,0:07:45.22,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,but no they left behind 12 of the 14 taken on the Apollo missions.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:45.66,0:07:49.50,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,宇航员按照指示，只带回了胶卷盒
Dialogue: 2,0:07:45.66,0:07:49.50,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,The astronauts were instructed to bring back just the film canisters
Dialogue: 1,0:07:49.50,0:07:53.00,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,而不带回相机，从而为月球岩石样本留下空间
Dialogue: 2,0:07:49.50,0:07:53.00,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,and leave the cameras to make room for rock samples.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:53.22,0:07:59.58,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这使得六次任务可以多带回25千克的岩石
Dialogue: 2,0:07:53.22,0:07:59.58,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,This allowed an extra 25 kilograms of rocks to be brought back over six missions in place of the cameras.
Dialogue: 1,0:07:59.98,0:08:03.02,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,当然，有些东西太大了带不回去
Dialogue: 2,0:07:59.98,0:08:03.02,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Of course some things were just far too big to bring back
Dialogue: 1,0:08:03.02,0:08:06.72,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,比如三个月球车和上面的摄影机
Dialogue: 2,0:08:03.02,0:08:06.72,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,like the three lunar Rovers along with their TV cameras.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:06.88,0:08:11.74,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,它们留在月球表面，由地球远程操控拍摄宇航员从月球起飞的画面
Dialogue: 2,0:08:06.88,0:08:11.74,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,They were left behind to film the ascent from a Moon by remote control on Earth.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:11.98,0:08:14.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,还有一个镀金的望远镜
Dialogue: 2,0:08:11.98,0:08:14.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,There was also a gold-plated telescope,
Dialogue: 1,0:08:14.24,0:08:19.48,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,唯一一个地球以外的星球表面观测太空的望远镜
Dialogue: 2,0:08:14.24,0:08:19.48,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,the only one to make observations from a surface of a celestial body other than the Earth.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:19.70,0:08:24.78,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有一些象征性的东西，通常不是官方批准的东西
Dialogue: 2,0:08:19.70,0:08:24.78,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Other things left behind were symbolic in nature and were not always officially sanctioned.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:25.38,0:08:32.16,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗11号除了国旗，还留下了一个黄金橄榄枝以表示和平
Dialogue: 2,0:08:25.38,0:08:32.16,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,We all know the U.S. flags but Apollo 11 also left behind a gold olive branch as a representation of peace.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:32.36,0:08:38.70,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还留下了阿波罗1号的徽章，纪念死于训练中火灾的三位宇航员
Dialogue: 2,0:08:32.36,0:08:38.70,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,An Apollo 1 patch to honor the crew of Grissom, White and Chaffey who died in a fire during testing,
Dialogue: 1,0:08:38.98,0:08:43.98,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有纪念已去世的宇航员加加林和科马洛夫的奖牌
Dialogue: 2,0:08:38.98,0:08:43.98,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and medals given to the families of the deceased cosmonauts Gagarin and Komarov.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:44.66,0:08:46.94,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有一个月球纪念盘
Dialogue: 2,0:08:44.66,0:08:46.94,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,There is also the Moon memorial disc
Dialogue: 1,0:08:46.94,0:08:52.44,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,上面有艾森豪威尔、肯尼迪、约翰逊、尼克松总统的友好致辞
Dialogue: 2,0:08:46.94,0:08:52.44,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,which contained the goodwill statements by President Eisenhower, Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon
Dialogue: 1,0:08:52.44,0:08:56.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有当时世界上73个国家领导人的致辞
Dialogue: 2,0:08:52.44,0:08:56.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and messages from the leaders of 73 countries from around the world.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:56.78,0:09:00.72,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,盘片制作技术类似早期的集成电路
Dialogue: 2,0:08:56.78,0:09:00.72,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The disc was made using the same techniques as early integrated circuits
Dialogue: 1,0:09:01.04,0:09:07.28,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,大小和50美分硬币差不多，用显微镜可以看到书写内容
Dialogue: 2,0:09:01.04,0:09:07.28,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and is the size of a U.S. 50-cent coin with the writing visible using a microscope.
Dialogue: 1,0:09:07.82,0:09:13.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,阿波罗15号中留下了一个称为“倒下的宇航员”的9厘米雕塑和一个石碑
Dialogue: 2,0:09:07.82,0:09:13.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,On Apollo 15 a nine centimeter statue called "Fallen Astronaut" along with a plaque
Dialogue: 1,0:09:13.96,0:09:19.04,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,135,,以此纪念14名苏联和美国在航天飞行或训练过程中牺牲的宇航员
Dialogue: 2,0:09:13.96,0:09:19.04,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,100,,commemorating the 14 US and Soviet astronauts which died during training
Dialogue: 1,0:09:19.04,0:09:22.34,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,并由宇航员大卫·斯科特非正式地放在了月球表面
Dialogue: 2,0:09:19.04,0:09:22.34,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,was unofficially placed on the Moon by David Scott.
Dialogue: 1,0:09:22.62,0:09:28.92,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,{\fs61}在阿波罗16号任务中，查尔斯·杜克将他和妻子、两个女儿的照片留在月球
Dialogue: 2,0:09:22.62,0:09:28.92,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,And on Apollo 16 Charlie Duke left a photo of himself his wife and two children on the surface.
Dialogue: 1,0:09:29.16,0:09:30.42,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,照片背面写道
Dialogue: 2,0:09:29.16,0:09:30.42,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,On the back he wrote
Dialogue: 1,0:09:40.26,0:09:42.36,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,在阿波罗任务期间与之后
Dialogue: 2,0:09:40.26,0:09:42.36,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,During and after the Apollo missions,
Dialogue: 1,0:09:42.36,0:09:49.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,苏联在1970-1973年间仍在进行可远程控制的月球步行者1、2号任务
Dialogue: 2,0:09:42.36,0:09:49.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the Soviets continued with their remote-controlled lunokhod Rovers 1 and 2 in 1970 and 1973.
Dialogue: 1,0:09:49.82,0:09:59.98,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,{\fs61}月球步行者2号运行4个月，行进42公里，传回86张全景照片和八万张照片
Dialogue: 2,0:09:49.82,0:09:59.98,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Lunokhod 2 operated for four months traveling 42 kilometers and sending back 86 panoramicimages and 80,000 TV pictures.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:00.34,0:10:05.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,从那以后就只有来自美国、日本、印度和中国的卫星了
Dialogue: 2,0:10:00.34,0:10:05.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Since then there have only been satellites from the US, Japan, India and China
Dialogue: 1,0:10:05.48,0:10:07.76,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,它们多数是最终坠毁在月球表面
Dialogue: 2,0:10:05.48,0:10:07.76,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,most of which have ended up on the surface,
Dialogue: 1,0:10:07.94,0:10:13.40,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,直到2013年12月，中国的嫦娥3号和玉兔号使之成为世界第三个
Dialogue: 2,0:10:07.94,0:10:13.40,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,until December 2013 when the Chinese became only the third country
Dialogue: 1,0:10:13.40,0:10:20.00,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,成功进行月球软着陆的国家
Dialogue: 1,0:10:13.40,0:10:20.00,1080P_CN_Up,,0,0,0,,原视频口误说成嫦娥四号，实际上指的是嫦娥三号
Dialogue: 2,0:10:13.40,0:10:20.00,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,to soft land on the Moon with the Chang'e 3 and the Yutu or Jade rabbit Rover.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:20.00,0:10:26.62,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,虽然月球车两个月后因为月尘导致的机械故障无法工作
Dialogue: 2,0:10:20.00,0:10:26.62,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Although the rover succumbed to a mechanical abnormality probably caused by the lunar dust after two months,
Dialogue: 1,0:10:26.78,0:10:32.24,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但着陆器本身自带放射性同位素热电机与太阳能电池
Dialogue: 2,0:10:26.78,0:10:32.24,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,the lander which is powered by radioisotope thermoelectric generator and solar cells
Dialogue: 1,0:10:32.48,0:10:37.58,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,使其着陆四年半后与地面控制中心有联系
Dialogue: 2,0:10:32.48,0:10:37.58,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,was still in contact with the ground control some four and a half years after it landed,
Dialogue: 1,0:10:37.58,0:10:41.68,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,并且它的能源理论上仍能坚持30年
Dialogue: 2,0:10:37.58,0:10:41.68,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and in theory its power supply could last for 30 years.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:42.32,0:10:45.16,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,那么月球上这些东西结局会如何？
Dialogue: 2,0:10:42.32,0:10:45.16,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,So what will happen to the things left on the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:45.26,0:10:49.56,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,有些人说月球没有各种侵蚀作用、风化、雨水或者火山活动
Dialogue: 2,0:10:45.26,0:10:49.56,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Some say that with no erosion, no wind, rain or volcanic activity,
Dialogue: 1,0:10:49.78,0:10:53.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,它们活的会比人类还长
Dialogue: 2,0:10:49.78,0:10:53.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,they will be there long after the human race has come to an end
Dialogue: 1,0:10:53.44,0:10:58.82,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,未来上百万甚至数十亿年不变，但他们忽略了几个问题
Dialogue: 2,0:10:53.44,0:10:58.82,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,in the millions or even billions of years into the future, but they are forgetting a few things.
Dialogue: 1,0:10:59.32,0:11:06.92,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,首先是月尘，月尘覆盖整个月球表面，且仍在因陨石撞击而生成
Dialogue: 2,0:10:59.32,0:11:06.92,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Firstly the lunar dust, it covers the entire Moon and was created and still is being created by meteor impact.
Dialogue: 1,0:11:07.34,0:11:09.75,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,虽然月球上没有吹动它们的风
Dialogue: 2,0:11:07.34,0:11:09.75,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Although there is no wind to move it around,
Dialogue: 1,0:11:09.75,0:11:14.84,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但它们会因太阳紫外、X波段辐射而带电
Dialogue: 2,0:11:09.75,0:11:14.84,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,it becomes electrostatically charged from the Sun's ultraviolet and x-ray radiation.
Dialogue: 1,0:11:15.12,0:11:20.00,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,导致其漂浮空中，形成极其稀薄的月尘大气
Dialogue: 2,0:11:15.12,0:11:20.00,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,This causes it to levitate and create a very thin atmosphere of dust,
Dialogue: 1,0:11:20.20,0:11:27.92,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,持续随着月球昼夜交替在晨昏线附近升起落下
Dialogue: 2,0:11:20.20,0:11:27.92,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,constantly rising and falling around the terminator line as it sweeps across the surface from lunar day to lunar night.
Dialogue: 1,0:11:28.32,0:11:35.74,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,最近的研究实验表明月尘积累速度大约是每千年一毫米
Dialogue: 2,0:11:28.32,0:11:35.74,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Recent observations and experiments show that the dust builds up at a rate of around about one millimeter per thousand years.
Dialogue: 1,0:11:35.96,0:11:40.28,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,听上去挺慢的，但在一百万年内
Dialogue: 2,0:11:35.96,0:11:40.28,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Now that sounds like a tiny amount but in a million years,
Dialogue: 1,0:11:40.66,0:11:44.64,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,月球上所有东西都会掩埋在一米的月尘下方
Dialogue: 2,0:11:40.66,0:11:44.64,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,all the items on the Moon would be under a meter of dust,
Dialogue: 1,0:11:44.86,0:11:48.08,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这只是假设我们什么都不做防止情况恶化的前提下
Dialogue: 2,0:11:44.86,0:11:48.08,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and that's assuming we didn't do anything to make it worse.
Dialogue: 1,0:11:48.66,0:11:54.68,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,如果我们未来在月球采矿，扬起的月尘会越来越多
Dialogue: 2,0:11:48.66,0:11:54.68,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,If we start mining on the Moon then the amount of dust raised will be much much more,
Dialogue: 1,0:11:54.92,0:12:00.50,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,借助六分之一的重力与无空气阻力的环境，它们能飘非常的远
Dialogue: 2,0:11:54.92,0:12:00.50,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and with only one-sixth gravity and no air resistance it could also travel a very long way.
Dialogue: 1,0:12:00.98,0:12:04.54,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,另一个因素是太阳，月球没有地球那样保护自身的大气层
Dialogue: 2,0:12:00.98,0:12:04.54,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,Then there is the Sun, with no protective atmosphere like the Earth,
Dialogue: 1,0:12:04.54,0:12:11.96,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,表面所有东西都完全暴露在太阳的紫外、X波段射线和带电粒子下
Dialogue: 2,0:12:04.54,0:12:11.96,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,anything on the surface is exposed to the full force of the Sun's ultraviolet, x-ray and ionizing charged particles
Dialogue: 1,0:12:12.32,0:12:17.56,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,想想那些被太阳暴晒的照片和涂料的下场就知道了
Dialogue: 2,0:12:12.32,0:12:17.56,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,just look at its effect here on Earth on paint pigments and photos that have been left out in the Sun.
Dialogue: 1,0:12:18.16,0:12:22.62,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,没有大气的另一个问题是温度
Dialogue: 2,0:12:18.16,0:12:22.62,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,That lack of atmosphere also means there is almost no temperature regulation
Dialogue: 1,0:12:22.82,0:12:31.60,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,太阳直射月球温度可达到127°C，晚上则能下降到-173°C
Dialogue: 2,0:12:22.82,0:12:31.60,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,so in direct sunlight the surface can reach a 127 °C and at night it can drop to minus 173 °C.
Dialogue: 1,0:12:31.98,0:12:38.74,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这上下三百摄氏度的温差就够月表那些东西喝一壶的了
Dialogue: 2,0:12:31.98,0:12:38.74,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The thermal stress of that 300 degree temperature range would also take its toll on anything left there.
Dialogue: 1,0:12:39.24,0:12:45.26,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,查尔斯·杜克47年前留下的照片估计早就完全褪色了
Dialogue: 2,0:12:39.24,0:12:45.26,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,The photo that Charlie Duke left 47 years ago is probably completely bleached by now
Dialogue: 1,0:12:45.50,0:12:50.30,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,那些美国国旗和各种涂料的表面最终下场也差不多
Dialogue: 2,0:12:45.50,0:12:50.30,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,as are the U.S. flags and pigments and painted surfaces will have degraded
Dialogue: 1,0:12:50.48,0:12:57.60,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,还有一个因素是微陨石直接撞击或落在附近
Dialogue: 2,0:12:50.48,0:12:57.60,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and is also the sandblasting effect of micro meteorites hitting objects directly or nearby
Dialogue: 1,0:12:57.60,0:13:00.56,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,仍然会激起烦人的月尘
Dialogue: 2,0:12:57.60,0:13:00.56,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,and lunar dust which is highly abrasive.
Dialogue: 1,0:13:01.14,0:13:08.32,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,所以虽然相比放在地球，它们在月球表面可能活时间更长一点
Dialogue: 2,0:13:01.14,0:13:08.32,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,So while they may well in some ways last a lot longer than they would do compared to being left outside on Earth,
Dialogue: 1,0:13:08.60,0:13:13.46,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,但最终也逃不过相同的、化为尘埃的命运
Dialogue: 2,0:13:08.60,0:13:13.46,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,they will meet the same fate and eventually crumble to dust.
Dialogue: 1,0:13:14.00,0:13:17.94,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,阿波罗留在月球那么多东西的原因之一
Dialogue: 2,0:13:14.00,0:13:17.94,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,One of the reasons for Apollo leaving so much stuff on the Moon
Dialogue: 1,0:13:17.94,0:13:21.48,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,是他们可以带回登月舱上升级的重量是有限的
Dialogue: 2,0:13:17.94,0:13:21.48,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,was the limited weight they could carry back in the ascent module.
Dialogue: 1,0:13:21.66,0:13:27.84,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,要榨干每一千克的运力，他们就得决定什么留下什么带走
Dialogue: 2,0:13:21.66,0:13:27.84,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,With every kilogram making a difference they had to choose what to bring back and what to leave.
Dialogue: 1,0:13:28.36,0:13:32.10,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这只是登月计划中无数困难的冰山一角
Dialogue: 2,0:13:28.36,0:13:32.10,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,These were just some of the myriad of problems that had to be solved
Dialogue: 1,0:13:32.20,0:13:35.86,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,相比于整个任务，这些琐事关注度并不那么高
Dialogue: 2,0:13:32.20,0:13:35.86,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,often with very short notice on the missions themselves
Dialogue: 1,0:13:35.96,0:13:40.38,1080P_CN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,这不止是对于阿波罗任务，每个月球相关的任务都是这样
Dialogue: 2,0:13:35.96,0:13:40.38,1080P_EN_Bottom,,0,0,0,,not only for Apollo but for every lunar mission that's ever been attempted.
